---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="About | Jeff Conners" description="About the artist and process behind the collection.">
  <section class="hero flow-section flow-section--first reveal">
    <p class="section-label">About</p>
    <h1>
      Seeing differently,
      <span class="accent">painting honestly.</span>
    </h1>
    <p>
      Jeff Conners is partially colorblind. Instead of limiting his palette, it freed it — he paints
      what he feels in a scene rather than what convention says it should look like.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="about-portrait flow-section reveal">
    <div class="about-portrait__image">
      <picture>
        <source srcset="/jeff-painting.webp" type="image/webp" />
        <img src="/jeff-painting.jpg" alt="Jeff Conners painting at his easel" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1000" height="800" />
      </picture>
    </div>
    <div class="about-portrait__text">
      <p class="section-label">The Artist</p>
      <p>
        Jeff is currently the Artist in Residence at Elevator in North Kansas City.
        A self-taught artist, he works across watercolor, acrylics, and oils — specializing
        in city and urban life, slices of daily moments that tell a brief story in a single frame.
      </p>
      <p>
        Having recently moved from the San Francisco Bay Area to Kansas City, Jeff finds the
        Westport, Crossroads, and West Bottoms neighborhoods to be fascinating, inviting places
        to capture in his work.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="two-col flow-section reveal">
    <article class="panel">
      <p class="section-label">Process</p>
      <p>
        Acrylics, watercolors, oils, and ink across canvas and paper. Urban scenes dominate —
        rain-soaked streets, neon intersections, silhouettes against city light — alongside
        landscapes, portraits, and the occasional quiet moment between storms.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article class="panel">
      <p class="section-label">The Eye</p>
      <p>
        The work lives in contrasts that shouldn't work together but do — electric green
        rain, blue towers against red sky, violet hours that exist nowhere in nature.
        Partial colorblindness isn't a limitation here. It's the entire point of view.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="about-portrait flow-section reveal" style="flex-direction:row-reverse;">
    <div class="about-portrait__image">
      <picture>
        <source srcset="/jeff-portrait.webp" type="image/webp" />
        <img src="/jeff-portrait.jpg" alt="Jeff Conners" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="800" height="800" />
      </picture>
    </div>
    <div class="about-portrait__text">
      <p class="section-label">Beyond the Canvas</p>
      <p>
        Along with painting and visual arts, Jeff has a long background in the theatrical arts
        as an actor and director, having recently directed <em>Bullshot Crummond</em> at
        the Roaring 20 Gallery and Art in Kansas City.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a class="cta" href="https://artskcgo.com/artist/jeff-conners" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View on ArtsKC</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
